observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management review the existing practices in conducting physical count of its PPE and maintaining property and accounting records to address the noted deficiencies. We further recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE):

Require the Inventory Committee (IC) to (a) ensure that subsequent additions or improvements to single PPE items are consolidated and reflected within the main PPE item, rather than listed as additional PPE items, (b) include necessary information in the RPCPPE to assist users, examiners, and other stakeholders in verifying and tracing the items listed in the report and (c) review and reassess the previously conducted physical count of PPE accounts, particularly focusing on why certain PPE items were listed with no details as to its location;

Instruct the Municipal General Services Office (MGSO) to maintain PCs in accordance with the MNGAS for LGUs and affix property stickers to each unit of PPE;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain PPELCs. Additionally, we recommended that PPELCs for all PPE items be created and maintained with complete information in accordance with the requirement of the MNGAS for LGUs;

Implement the provisions of Section 5.3 of COA Circular No. 2020-006, which mandates that all IC members should be temporarily relieved from their regular responsibilities to focus entirely on conducting the physical inventory until its completion;

Instruct key LGU personnel and officers to supervise the completion of the donation process of property to the respective barangays. This involves furnishing a property list, requesting approval for donation resolutions from the Sangguniang Bayan (SB), and fulfilling other essential steps; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare adjusting entries in the books to reflect the derecognition of these properties from the Municipal Government of Bulan (MGB) records once documentary requirements are completed. Alternatively, ensure that disclosures are made in the Notes to the Financial Statements (FS) regarding any PPE recorded in the books of MGB but are currently controlled and utilized by other LGUs.

We recommended that the LCE:

Conduct a re-orientation workshop or seminar for accountable officers (AOs) on the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002, dated February 10, 1997, and other relevant rules and guidelines governing the granting, utilization, and liquidation of CAs;

Develop or improve current internal policies to closely monitor AOs’ compliance with the rules and guidelines governing CAs. This includes issuing an Executive Order (EO) to the Municipal Accountant to withhold the salary of AOs who fail to liquidate their CAs within the prescribed timeframe, as stipulated in Section 5.9 of COA Circular No. 97-002;

Require the Municipal Accountant to submit copies of the demand letters sent to non-LGU personnel, along with their replies and justifications, for verification and validation by the AT. Additionally, we recommended that Management cease granting CAs to non-LGU personnel, particularly those who are not bonded, as this lack of bonding makes it difficult to properly monitor and control these CAs;

Require AOs to submit a list of expenses charged against previous unliquidated CAs before the start of the ensuing year, thereby providing the Municipal Accountant with the option to disclose any unliquidated CAs at year-end in the Notes to the FS, which expenses had been incurred; and

In cases where all administrative remedies have been exhausted and the liquidation of the subject CAs appear remote, we recommended that Management apply for request for write-off of these dormant unliquidated CAs accompanied by the necessary documents in compliance with the provisions stated in COA Circular No. 2023-008 dated August 17, 2023.

We recommended that the LCE:

Require the Human Resources and Management Office (HRMO) to assess the existing Organizational Structure, expedite filling up the vacant positions thru advertisement and assessment of qualified employees for promotion, and submit a report thereon to the LCE for approval by appropriate bodies;

Require strict adherence to the written policy/guidelines by the HRMO and other relevant department units to address effectively the necessity and appropriateness of hiring JO workers, ensuring that they do not undertake tasks assigned to existing permanent and regular employees as outlined in their respective job descriptions.

Implement an effective performance evaluation mechanism, as directed by EO 58, to ensure that the rehiring process aligns with the actual necessity of the LGU;

Limit the hiring/deployment to those offices that are actually extremely in need of their services;

Require that all department heads and immediate supervisors provide the HRMO with copy of the written work schedule to facilitate effective monitoring of job performance in adherence to the policy guidelines.

We recommended that Management:

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to continue and strengthen coordination with the Municipal Engineer to determine the condition of the infrastructure assets constructed in CYs 2015 and below, in order to assess the carrying amounts of the said assets and effect the necessary adjustments in the books to arrive at a more reliable Infrastructure Asset accounts balance in the FS; and

Require the Municipal Engineer to provide the IC with complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects to facilitate the preparation of RPCLRN;

We recommended that the Management:
a. Direct the Municipal Accountant to provide reconciliation on the noted understatement of the PPE accounts;
b. Direct the General Services Officer (GSO) to conduct a complete physical inventory of all PPE of the Municipality;
c. Direct the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the differences noted between the records of GSO and the Accounting Office;
d. Conduct the disposal procedure for the unserviceable PPE and derecognize the same from the books; and
e. Prepare adjusting entries to reflect the correct balance of the CIP.

We reiterated that Management require the:
a. coordination between the Municipal Accountant and the GSO towards the full implementation of the perpetual inventory method in recording of supplies and materials; and establishment of sufficient stock room for proper storage of items of inventories;
b. GSO-designate/Inventory Committee to prepare and submit a complete Report on the Physical Count of Inventories semestrally in order to determine the correctness of the recorded inventories in the books of accounts of the Municipality and to ensure that semestral count of Inventory items is promptly conducted and the corresponding report is submitted on time to the Audit Team;
c. Municipal Accountant and GSO to maintain supplies ledger cards (SLC) and stock cards (SC), respectively, for each type of inventories and reconcile the accounting and property records periodically to bring these accounts into agreement; and
d. MGSO to prepare and maintain Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) for each item of inventory with shelf life of more than one year to establish proper accountability of accountable officers concerned.

We recommended that the Management:
a. Prioritize the establishment of an environmentally compliant sanitary landfill;
b. Ensure thorough planning of procurement for hauling services and maintain complete documentation for all disbursements;
c. Review and reconcile the payment for the hauling services provided by the private sanitary landfill corporation to ensure accurate billing and payment and take appropriate action to prevent potential disputes or claims;
d. Use the Environment / Sanitary Services (50212010) account in recognizing the cost of garbage and hospital waste collection and disposal; and
e. Strictly comply with the environmental laws outlined in R.A. No. 9003.

We recommended that Management:
a. Direct the HRMO to submit to the Audit Team the basis/memorandum approved and signed by the Municipal Mayor approving the salary increase;
b. HRMO to explain the inconsistencies in the role assignment on identified JO workers;
c. Require the HRMO to ensure formal documentation of any rate changes through signed contract amendments before processing payroll adjustments, and to submit these to the Audit Team promptly as the situation arises; and
d. Direct MACCO to conduct monthly reconciliation between contract terms and payroll records to ensure that the rate being paid aligns with the rate stated in the signed contract.

We recommended that Management:
a. Prepare an Organizational Structure and Staffing Pattern Plan, and formulate policies and guidelines so that the necessity and propriety of hiring job order employees are justified;
b. Review, along with the department heads, the current manpower matrix to ensure that the hiring and engagement of job orders are in accordance with the needs of the Municipality;
c. Provide the Office of the Auditor with a Certification by the Local Chief Executive/Personnel Officer that the activities/ services to be rendered by the COS and JO workers cannot be provided by regular or permanent personnel of the LGU; and
d. Require the Accounting Office and the Human Resource Management Office to ensure that required supporting documents for claims particularly for first claims of the JO workers are attached to the payroll.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Direct the IC to conduct complete physical count of all inventories in accordance with the prescribed rules;
Require the MGSO to maintain complete and appropriate SCs for each type of supplies and materials;
Conduct regular reconciliation of the SLCs and SCs to ensure that all purchases and issuances are properly accounted for; and
Require the MAO to record inventory using the prescribed perpetual inventory method to ensure reliability and accuracy of the accounts presented in the FS.

We recommended that Management:

Require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Engineer to reconcile their respective records concerning the status and incurred costs of ongoing projects under the MGB;

Direct the Bids and Awards Committee to efficiently complete all documentary requirements for each project to prevent bottlenecks in payments and ensure the smooth transfer of CIP balances to the appropriate PPE accounts;

Require the Municipal Engineer’s Office to promptly furnish the Quarterly Report on Government Projects/Programs/Activities (GPPAs) to the Municipal Accountant’s Office (MAO), ensuring the timely inclusion of any pertinent information regarding the CIP accounts in the Notes to the FS; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant to adjust the CIP accounts to accurately reflect their balances, or alternatively, make appropriate disclosures in the Notes to the FS regarding the circumstances surrounding these balances.

We recommended that Management:

Increase the bonding requirement for some Special Disbursement Officers (SDOs) to ensure sufficient coverage for CAs. This measure addresses the issue of limited personnel handling CAs and expedites completion of priority PPAs while ensuring compliance with the provisions outlined in Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and Section 5 of COA Circular No. 97-002;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to consider withholding the salary of AOs who fail to liquidate their CAs within the prescribed timeframe as prescribed by Section 5.9 of COA Circular No. 97-002;

Require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to retrieve information related to outstanding CAs from journals, cashbooks, and reports of checks issued. These secondary evidences will serve as a crucial source of information for identifying and tracking the status of outstanding CAs especially those that were granted in prior years; and

In cases where all administrative remedies have been exhausted and the liquidation of the subject CAs appear remote, we recommended that Management apply for request for write-off of these dormant unliquidated CAs accompanied by the necessary documents in compliance with the provisions stated in COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

16. We recommended that the LDRRMO coordinate with the OCD on the preparation and submission of the Municipality’s PSCP pursuant to NDRRMC Memorandum No 33, s. 2018.
17. We further recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:
a) To conduct risk assessment;
b) To identify critical processes and functions;
c) To determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation;
d) To conduct risk analysis and impact analysis;
e) To formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed templates and requirements in the PSCP guidebook; and
f) To submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the Local Chief Executive for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
require the GSO to conduct on time the physical inventory of all its PPE and prepare and submit the RPCPPE not later than January 31 of the ensuing year;
require that MA and GSO to maintain the pertinent property records and reconciliation between the records of both offices be undertaken and effect the necessary adjustments in the accounting books to fairly present the said accounts in the financial statements;
require the GSO to maintain the pertinent reports and property records of Road Networks to be able to provide reliable basis on the amounts presented in the financial statements;
require Municipal Accountant to disclose in the Notes to FS the road network system; and
instruct the Municipal Assessor and other officials concerned to prioritize and facilitate the titling of these parcels of land in order to establish absolute ownership and protect the legal interest of the LGU thereon.

We recommended that Management:
require the concerned officers and employees to immediately settle/liquidate their outstanding cash advances through the submission of duly accomplished liquidation reports, otherwise, enforce the withholding of salary, in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002;
stop the grant of additional cash advances to all personnel with unliquidated cash advances until such time previous cash advances are fully settled, and see to it that officials and employees who seek transfer to other offices or those filing for terminal leaves are not given certificates of clearance until their balances are paid;
request for the write-off of dormant accounts in accordance with COA Circular No. 2016-005, if applicable;
prepare and maintain complete and updated SLs, ageing and other subsidiary records of the accounts presented in the FS in accordance with Section 10 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Volume II; and
monitor and establish controls to ensure the timely liquidation of cash advances through updated monthly ageing of the same to prevent accumulation of unliquidated cash advances and ensure that the rules and regulations on the grant of cash advances are strictly observed.

We recommended that Management require the:
Municipal Treasurer to prepare yearly a duly certified list of taxpayers based on the updated RPTARs showing the names of the taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year, and furnish the same to the Municipal Accounting Office at the beginning of every fiscal year;
Municipal Accountant to record RPT/SET Receivable yearly based on the duly certified list provided by the MTO;
Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain both the JEVs and the Abstract of RPT Collections in accordance with the provisions of GAAM and Manual on the NGAS for LGUs; and
Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to conduct periodic reconciliation of their records in order to come up with accurate and reliable reports on the levy of RPT and SET.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
liquidate fund transfers once projects are fully implemented and/or refund the unutilized amount from completed projects and require the appropriate recording in the books of accounts;
prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers for the total balance of ₱1,451,780.54 as of December 31, 2021, otherwise, provide adequate disclosure in the notes to financial statements.

We recommended that management:
Ensure that the LCE’s authority to hire and engage JO workers are within the ambit of good governance, administrative necessity and fiscal adequacy of the LGU;
Formulate uniform policy and procedures in engaging and managing JO workers taking into consideration the existing law, rules and regulations;
Conduct personnel audit, review, assessment and evaluation of the existing manpower complement of the LGU so as to determine the necessity and propriety of engaging JO workers;
Use appropriate forms of contract stipulating the duties and responsibilities of the JO, the expected output and deliverables and the standard wage rates; and
Strictly comply with the documentary requirements in COA Circular      2012-001.

We recommended that Management:

require the Municipal Accountant to send demand letters to the concerned Accountable Officers (AOs) requesting immediate liquidation of the cash advance or settlement of the amounts due from them;

suspend the salaries of erring accountable officers until such time that full settlement of their cash advances are effected; 

stop the practice of granting cash advances to officials and employees unless the previous ones are fully liquidated; and

ensure that rules and regulations on the grant of cash advances are strictly observed.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor  instruct  the Municipal Accountant and the LDRRMO  to 
ensure the submission of genuine, original and complete documentary requirements to establish the validity of transactions;
appoint a documenter to any training conducted as proof of occurrence of the training;
choose lecturers with expertise;
utilize the re-echo strategy to minimize sending big delegation to trainings and desist from conducting training in places outside the official station;
support purchases out of calamity fund  with original and signed distribution lists, RIV and ARE ; 
avoid excessive procurement by purchasing  quantity of supplies commensurate to  the needs of  requisitioners;
require  submission of RIS and Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment  to document receipt by  recipients of calamity supplies and equipment; and
limit charges against the LDDRMF  only to  disaster related programs, projects and activities.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor;
require the Local Finance Committee to provide appropriations for the titling of all land holdings of the Municipality;
require the Municipal Assessor to work for the titling of the 30  lots with tax declarations in the name of the Municipality; and
Municipal Accountant to recognize the value of the nine school lots valued at ₱2,168,280.00in the Land account to be able to present fairly the asset and the equity account in the financial statements.

We recommended that Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Treasurer to;
to settle her accountabilities; and
to adhere strictly to applicable laws, rules and regulation affecting cash advances.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the;
Local School Board to ensure that only the authorized priority expenditures identified under the SEF mandate are planned and programmed in the SEF Annual Budget;
Municipal Budget Officer desist from improperly charging non-priority expenditures against the SEF; and
Municipal Accountant to ensure that payments of expenditures are in accordance with the top priorities of the SEF.

We recommended that Management 
provide adequate and realistic budget for its GAD Plan by including therein only programs/projects/activities that promote gender-responsive governance, protect and fulfill women’s rights and promote women’s activities;
require the  Municipal Budget Officer and the GAD Focal Person to desist from charging  non-related  expenditures against the GAD Fund which did not partake of the nature of GAD programs, projects and activities;
establish sex disaggregated data to institutionalize and improve GAD planning and budgeting; and
enact a GAD Code and implement a comprehensive and sustainable GAD programs.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor  enforce  full  compliance  with the Ecological Solid Waste Management Act of 2000  by;
requiring the Solid Waste Management Board to complete the preparation of the ten-year Solid Waste Management Plan;
directing  strict enforcement by  households  with  wastes segregation  at source and implementing the No Segregation No Collection Policy ;
enjoining  all barangays to establish their own Materials Recovery Facility and 
instructing the MENRO to be aggressive in the implementation  of concrete projects for solid waste avoidance and volume reduction through source reduction and waste minimization measures in order the reduce expenses for tipping fees.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive
require the Accountant and the Treasurer to stop the payment of annual dues to various organizations and associations not in conformity with R.A. No. 7160 for lack of legal basis;
require the Municipal Budget Officer to refrain from obligating claims without the available appropriations for the purpose; 
advise the Municipal Accountant to see to it that claims for the membership, dues, and contributions be substantiated with the necessary budget and approved plans and programs as basis for the amount to be paid; and
advise the Municipal Treasurer that payments for the purpose made to duly recognized leagues and federations under the law be acknowledged only with the prescribed government Accountable Form No. 51.
